WAT.ai is recruiting for Director positions! WAT.ai is both the Undergraduate Body of the Waterloo A.I. Institute and a member of the Sedra Student Design Centre. The Waterloo AI Forum is a one-of-a-kind debate at UW on Saturday, March 9th. They have spots for 40 students to share their perspectives on how AI should affect our society! Introducing WAT.ai's latest project: Mechanistic Interpretability!The project focuses on training a simple transformer to understand basic arithmetic operations and analyze its learning mechanisms, including the identification of polysemantic or superposition neurons.By examining the transformer's behavior and employing a sparse autoencoder, we aim to transform complex activations into interpretable formats. This research will provide insights into how neural networks generalize learning and enhance AI interpretability.Ultimately, this work seeks to bridge the gap between complex AI operations and human-understandable interpretations.Applications are open! If you have any questions feel free to reach out!Application link: https://forms.gle/aspSiAfgu2yYMwyh7(also in bio)Deadline: February 25, 2024

UW's first in person GIS day since 2019 will be taking place on November 15th between 1:00 and 4:00 PM in the Geospatial Centre (Dana Porter Library). There is a packed agenda of lightning talks and workshops this year (be sure to sign up using the link if you want to do a workshop), Google Earth VR will be on offer, and there will be free cake and coffee at the event. If you want to learn more about the exciting GIS projects that are happening all across campus or pick up some new GIS skills (e.g. Python in GIS and Web Mapping with JavaScript), this is the event for you!

The Conference on Diversity in Engineering Apllications are finally open!!TLDR:Dates: November 22nd to 25th, 2024Host: Western UniversityTheme: Re-Imagining EngineeringWebsite: cde.cfes.caLinkedIn: cde-cdi-2024Instagram: @cde.cdi.2024APPLY NOWWWWWThe Conference on Diversity in Engineering (CDE), formerly known as the National Conference on Women in Engineering (NCWIE) is an annual student-run conference of the CFES. The conference takes place nearing the end of November at that yearâ€™s respective host school. CDE aims to develop knowledge surrounding the variety of individuals, cultures and perspectives found within engineering communities. CDE further aims to instill a notion of positivity and togetherness in creating spaces that value the differences between groups of engineering students and professionals.Delegates will not only leave the conference with a solid understanding of the issues minorities encounter in the engineering profession, but they will also be equipped to appropriately address these issues to create a more inclusive and thriving community. Students attending CDE will have the opportunity to meet and hear from successful, interesting, and talented speakers prepared to share their experience and knowledge on how to embrace diversity in order to better address the complex, interdisciplinary problems of society.

Fall 24 By-Election Announcement!With the recent resignation of the A-Soc President, the executive team intents to hold a by-election to fill the role for the remainder of the term. As per Bylaw II Section J.3, seeing as the resigning president is within the final 8 months of their position, a motion will be presented at Council 1 (September 17th) for council to determine if a by-election is held. If the motion passes, a by-election will be held immediately following council's decision. The A-Soc VP Academic is intending to run for President. If elected, a by-election for the VP Academic position will also likely occur at Council 1. In the event this occurs, this notice also serves to solicit candidates for the secondary by-election at Council 1. For more information and eligibility requirements, please visit bit.ly/F24ByElection.For questions, please email cro.a@engsoc.uwaterloo.caPlease note the by-election is only to fill a vacancy on the current term. We thank Tyler for all his contribution to the society over the past 2 years, and wish him the best for his 4th year!

The Award, previously called the â€œTeaching Excellence Awardâ€, was renamed after Igor Ivkovic, a Systems Design Engineering Professor, who exemplified the spirit of the Award. Hundreds of students flock to line up for burgers, paint themselves purple and drop professors in the â€˜dunk tank.â€™â€¯â€¯ Engineering Day and other traditions within the faculty are critical in creating community and forging friendships and memories that will last a lifetime. Join us and campus wellness for speed friending! Thursday March 14th from 5:30 - 6:30 in POETS!Speed-friending is fun and friendly take on speed-dating, where the goal is to quickly make friends through engaging conversation. Participants will sit across from each other and have 5 minutes to introduce themselves and start a conversation. At the end of 5 minutes, participants will change seats and reintroduce themselves to a new person. This continues until you have met as many people as time allows. Bring your own inclusive and engaging conversation starters or use some of ours. At the end of the session, you can stick around and continue the conversation, or make plans to connect another day. Itâ€™s a fun and safe way to make friends from across the Faculty of Engineering.Registration linked in bio!

Each term, the Engineering Society allocates a certain percentage of the budget towards the Sponsorship Fund. This fund goes towards supporting University of Waterloo student teams and groups. All University of Waterloo student teams and groups are eligible to receive sponsorship. Any student team or group who is interested in applying to the fund should read the guide available here: linktr.ee/vpfinance.aAll applications are due March 10th, 2024

The Igor Ivkovic Teaching Excellence Award recognizes a teacher (professors, lecturers, or laboratory instructors) from the Faculty of Engineering for their contributions to ensuring academic success for their students. To nominate someone you believe deserves recognition go to https://bit.ly/IgorTEAW24. The submission deadline is March 10th, 2024.

The EngSoc Friend of Natalie award (previously known as the Friend of the Society award) recognizes a faculty/staff member (this includes TAs and lab instructors) from the Faculty of Engineering for their contributions to improving the mental health of their students. The Engineering Society Leadership Excellence Award recognizes excellent displays of leadership within the University, Faculty of Engineering or community at large. In the Winter term, one award is presented to a full-time undergraduate engineering student in 1B or higher. Candidates must have attained an average of 60% in their most recent academic term. The prize is $1000.To apply, submit a resume, a detailed description of all leadership roles undertaken and a letter explaining how your leadership roles have had an impact or importance to the University of Waterloo, the Faculty of Engineering, or the Waterloo community (1-5 pages). For full details, see https://www.engsoc.uwaterloo.ca/about/awards/. Applications can be submitted via e-mail to awards@engsoc.uwaterloo.ca. The deadline to apply is March 10th, 2024.

Application form for the Conference on Sustainability in Engineering:https://bit.ly/CSE2024AppsApplications are due January 8th, 2024 at 11:59 PM.The Conference On Sustainability in Engineering (CSE) is a four day national conference that brings over 200 engineering students from 43 academic institutions together to engage in a hands-on learning about sustainability in engineering and their daily lives. Hosted at a different universities each year, students are introduced to sustainability initiatives from across Canada and empowered to implement their learning in their in their own communities. CSE provides passionate students with the opportunity to network and learn from their peers, industry professionals, and academics through hands-on workshops, technical talks and social events. This year the conference is focusing on the idea of The Essential Engineer. This term, created by author Henry Petrovski, centers around the idea that science alone will not solve our most complex global issues. CSE aims to provide participants with a comprehensive understanding of engineering and technology, while encompassing the broader context that recognizes the social, economic, and colonial factors contributing to environmental degradation and climate change. Attendees will have the opportunity to explore this idea further by reflecting on their own interactions with such forces both in their professional and personal experiences. It will make tangible connections to the engineering industry and allow attendees to learn how to incorporate environmentally sustainable practices and perspectives into their future careers. The conference will occur in Toronto and be hosted by Toronto Metropolitan University from Feb 22-25. Here is the Pre-Delegate package for more information: https://bit.ly/CSE2024Pre-DelegatePackage Sound like something you're interested in? Please apply! If your application is selected, you may be asked to attend an interview.If you have any questions, please contact Maia Tse (vpcomm.a@engsoc.uwaterloo.ca) or Thomas Li (vpcomm.b@engsoc.uwaterloo.ca) .

Itâ€™s was incredible for our team to qualify and compete in FSGP for the first time in 5 years! It was a long journey for us 2.5 years ago when we started this project from nothing and we couldnâ€™t have been more proud of everyone that helped us build this solar car! Although we were not able to qualify for ASC, weâ€™re still happy with what we were able to achieve over the duration of Scrutineering and FSGP with 100km on the track and a fastest lap of 5:55. We learned a lot during competition and from talking to other teams so weâ€™ll be back with many ideas and improvements for our next car, MSXVI! As we look towards MSXVI, weâ€™re looking for eager new members to help us in this new chapter of the team. Looking forward to seeing everyone in the Fall Term for recruitment!!

Thrilled to be part of the inspiring Kitchener-Waterloo Canadian Association for Girls in Science (CAGIS) relaunch event! Last month, we introduced girls and gender-diverse youth to the real-life applications of renewable energy, guiding them through building their very own model solar cars. It was great to see that this event sparked interest in engineering amongst all the attendees, especially when they got up close with our full-sized solar car! Big thanks to @girlsinscience for this incredible opportunity to help inspire future changemakers!

Hey UW students!Save the date for Midnight Sun's First General Meeting on Saturday, September 7th, 2024, at 1:00 PM in E7, room 4043. For more info, check out our Instagram and website, or come visit us during the SDC showcase!Weâ€™re excited to see you there!

Day 7: The final day of FSGP is here! After two days on track MSXV drove a total of 20 laps (62 miles) with a fastest lap time of 5:55! Joining 24 other teams on the track, we also had the pleasure of interviewing with ABC WBKO news on solar cars. Various mechanical and electrical issues kept us off the track for a good portion of the day but the team pulled through to drive 14 laps on day 3. As we pack up and head to display day, we thank NCM Motorsports park for being our home for the past 7 days!

Day 6: WE ARE ON THE TRACK! Despite some rough weather hitting the racetrack and significantly impacting most of the teams, MSXV raced itâ€™s first 3.1 miles today with Michael behind the wheel and the team has never been more excited to see it drive! Our time on track was limited, but MSXV finished the day with 6 laps completed and officially puts us on the scoreboard. Check out the video of our first lap!

Day 5: FSGP Race day is here! We gathered with the rest of the attending teams for a sunny team photo before getting right back to the pits for some last minute changes to push through dynamics. Michael was the first driver to be fully cleared to race, and our other two drivers cleared driver ops and are working to join the other teams out on the track!

FSGP Day 4: A lot of ups and downs through the last day before race kicks off. Red in mechanical was moved up to a yellow, slight issues in body and sizing and lights but we have hit green in all other categories. We were able to run through dynamics as well at the end of the day but will need to continue passing all drivers in dynamics tomorrow after race start. Youâ€™ll see us on the track soon!ğŸ“¸ @richard.w_144

FSGP Day 3: Scrutineering Day 2 is in full swing and we bumped a few more items off the checklist. Minor fixes were needed for electrical, while greens were picked up in Solar, BPS, and driver registration. Weâ€™re scheduled for mechanical and the remaining tomorrow with the hope that we can clear everything and hit dynamics before race start in 2 days!ğŸ“¸ @richard.w_144

FSGP DAY 2: Scrutineering begins! Team is completing all the last minute work and tune ups as we prepare to get assessed at the multiple scrutineering stations we need to clear to race. We unfortunately were not scheduled for many today, but picked up greens in Safety and Impound. 2 down 9 to go!ğŸ“¸ @richard.w_144

FSGP DAY 1: Load-in in Kentucky! We are attending for the first time since 2019 and the team has arrived safely on site, registered and are set up in the garage space we will be calling home for the next 7 days. 3 days of scrutineering and 3 days of racing lie ahead but the team is set and ready!ğŸ“¸ @richard.w_144 & @theroguecora

The second seminar coming up this week is SUPER intriguing! ğŸ‘¾Simran is hosting the second this week to investigate the role of cerebellum during a cross-modal attention blink task between vision and touch, make sure you tune in to both this week! ğŸ™Œ- --Presenter: Simran MughalDate: November 23rd, 2023 Time: 5:30PM - 7:30PMLocation: RCH 206 - - -Abstract: To achieve a unified perception of the external world and execute correct behaviours and or movements it is important to process different types of sensory inputs in (near-) unison to achieve maximal information of the environment. This is termed cross-modal integration of information. At any given time, the brain is exposed to a plethora of sensory stimuli and thus, relies on selection and task-relevance of information for successful integration. The concept of attention is not a singular system, but rather a collection of mechanisms and significant attributes within various perceptual and cognitive processes that enable the regulation of information processing. Interestingly, selection is one of the significant attributes of attentional control, through which the cognitive system determines the pertinent information for ongoing behaviour. According to current literature, there is evidence for the involvement of subcortical regions in attentional processing, such as the cerebellum. Traditionally, the cerebellum has been termed as an accessory motor structure and has been linked to motor control and coordination. Nevertheless, emerging evidence indicates that the cerebellar cortex possesses considerable heterogeneity in its anatomical and functional connections with regions outside the cerebellum.

Join us this Wednesday for this weekâ€™s first student seminar on the Visual Appearance of 3D objects in SR! ğŸªğŸš€ğŸ”­-Date: Wednesday November 15th, 2023Time: 5:30PM - 7:30PMLocation: PHY 352 -Abstract: The strange visual appearance of objects traveling near the speed of light is one of the puzzling predictions of Einstein's relativity. This is because the well-known Lorentz contraction of an object in relativity does not capture how an object would look - it doesn't take into account the time light takes to leave the object and reach the observer's eyes. We will derive a modified version of the Lorentz transformation which includes the time delay between measuring and seeing, followed by simulations of different objects traveling at high speeds. We also consider luminous objects, using the doppler effect to colour various objects while moving. We then talk about accelerating objects, whose visual appearance to an observer becomes extremely strange. Finally, we present some ideas about simulating the appearance of objects traveling in a strong gravitational field, moving from special to general relativity.

Join us for this weekâ€™s second seminar in RCH at 5:30PM ğŸ”­ğŸªğŸ›¸!More info and abstract below: Date: Thursday, November 16thLocation: RCH 206Time: 5:30 - 7:30 PM- - -Presenter: Siddhartha BhattacharjeeTitle: The Conservation of Mass isn't Fundamental in Classical Mechanics- - - Abstract:  In this seminar, we explore how the conservation of total mass of a closed system can be derived from simpler notions, namely Noether's theorem and the principle of relativity. This will be done using the Lagrangian formulation of classical mechanics.

Join us this Wednesday evening to listen to Shaeer Moeedâ€™s seminar this on Path Integrals and Statistical Mechanics this week! --Date: Wednesday, November 8th, 2023 Time: 5:30PM - 7:30PM Place: PHYS 352 More info:Path integrals allow us to extract equilibrium properties of quantum many body systems. In the past, they have to been used to further our understanding of superfluidity in condensed Helium as well as probe the quantum phase transitions in rotor lattices. We will first review the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics and discuss computational details pertaining to Path Integral Monte Carlo (PIMC) simulations. We will conclude with a discussion of recent work focused on optimizing the convergence of propagators used for PIMC. Time permitting, we will also examine the theory of superfluidity.

Hanuman Jayanti or Hanuman Janmotsav celebrates the birth of Lord Hanuman, the monkey God and an ardent follower of Shri Ram and Sita Mata, who played a significant role in helping Ram rescue Sita from the clutches of demon King Ravana. Considered an epitome of devotion, strength and selflessness, Lord Hanuman is known to offer solace and support to those in need. People visit temples on this day, pray to Lord Hanuman, give food to the needy, perform Sunder Kaand Paath, attend kirtans, recite bhajans, and more.

Ram Navami celebrates the birth of Lord Rama, the seventh incarnation of Lord Vishnu, who descended to Earth to restore dharma and vanquish evil. It marks the culmination of the nine-day festival of Chaitra Navratri. The story of Ramayana, his epic journey, and his triumph over the demon king Ravana serve as timeless reminders of righteousness, courage, and the victory of good over evil. On this auspicious day, devotees across the world engage in prayers, readings of scriptures, and reenactments of Ramaâ€™s life events. Itâ€™s a time to reflect on the values of truth, compassion, and devotion that Lord Rama exemplified, inspiring us to lead lives filled with righteousness and compassion. Happy Ram Navami to all!

As communities gather, laughter fills the air, and vibrant hues paint the streets, symbolizing unity, forgiveness, and the renewal of friendships. Maha Shivratri, meaning â€œGreat Night of Shiva,â€ is a Hindu festival dedicated to Lord Shiva. It commemorates the day when Shiva is believed to have performed the cosmic dance of creation, preservation, and destruction. Devotees fast, meditate, and offer prayers to seek blessings, symbolizing the triumph of light over darkness and knowledge over ignorance.Maha Shivratri is also associated with the celestial union of Lord Shiva and Goddess Parvati. According to Hindu mythology, this day marks the convergence of Shiva and Parvati as a divine couple. Devotees celebrate this cosmic union, portraying the harmonious balance between masculine and feminine energies.

This event fosters a collective sentiment of celebration and spiritual fulfillment, resonating with Hindus globally who view Ayodhya as a symbol of their shared cultural and religious roots. Kali Chaudas, also known as Narak Chaturdashi, is a Hindu festival observed on the 14th day of the dark fortnight in the month of Ashwin. Falling just before Diwali, it holds cultural significance as devotees engage in rituals to ward off evil and celebrate the victory of light over darkness. Traditionally, lamps are lit, symbolizing the dispelling of ignorance, and prayers are offered to Goddess Kali for protection. The day is marked by a spirit of purification, with people often engaging in rituals like bathing before sunrise and applying oil to their bodies. As families come together to celebrate the triumph of good over evil, Kali Chaudas serves as a prelude to the grandeur of Diwali, fostering a sense of spiritual cleansing and renewal. #KaliChaudas #NarakChaturdashi #IndianFestivals #DiwaliPreparations

Dhanteras, a significant Hindu festival, marks the auspicious beginning of Diwali celebrations. It holds immense cultural and spiritual importance. On this day, devotees worship Lord Dhanvantari, the god of health, and invest in precious metals like gold and silver, symbolizing prosperity and wealth. The tradition of buying new utensils also signifies the belief in attracting good fortune. As we light lamps and embrace the spirit of abundance, may this Dhanteras illuminate your life with joy, wealth, and well-being. Wishing you and your loved ones a prosperous and blissful Dhanteras!

Date: Monday, April 29Time 1:30PM - 2:30PMLocation: EIT 3142Â Abstract: In recent years, the integration of artificial intelligence (AI) into mechatronics systems has demonstrated significant promise across diverse industries, including manufacturing automation, smart manufacturing, and aerospace engineering. However, ensuring the reliability and trustworthiness of AI procedures, particularly in sensitive manufacturing applications, remains a critical challenge. In this research seminar, I will address the issue of guaranteeing AI procedures through hybrid control methods, which facilitate the development of certified learning algorithms essential for ensuring dependable performance in complex mechatronic systems. Furthermore, I will explore how adversarial machine learning techniques can enhance safety and security in control procedures for manufacturing and aerospace applications. Through these discussions, we aim to advance the application of AI in critical industrial domains while ensuring robustness and reliability in operational outcomes.The seminar explores the practical implications of these methodologies, demonstrating their potential to advance manufacturing automation, optimize smart manufacturing processes, and fortify control systems in aerospace engineering. By examining the intersection of certified learning and adversarial machine learning with mechatronics, this presentation illuminates innovative pathways toward enhancing efficiency, safety, and resilience across vital industrial sectors.#foryou #ai #viral #explore #explorepage #explorepageâœ¨ #exploremore #fyp #fypã‚· #tech #data #podcast #cs #health #healthtech #trendingreels #future #waterloo #canada #university #unilife #stem #womeninai

Inspired by the medical bay of the USS Enterprise from â€œStar Trekâ€, a research team from the University of Waterloo uses radar technology to monitor peopleâ€™s health while at the wheel, turning an ordinary car or truck into a mobile medical hub.Dr. George Shaker, an adjunct professor in the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering at the University of Waterloo, is working with a team of graduate students to integrate radar with evolving vehicle technology to make health checks easier. The idea is to use the time people spend in their cars to gather data on their health for accurate analysis and proactive treatment â€” without the need for any type of wearable.The radar, smaller than a USB thumb drive, is integrated into the vehicle cabin and sends out signals that detect human vibrations, which are then sent back to the radar. The built-in AI system collects and analyzes the data to build a medical picture and identify any potential conditions. At the end of the driverâ€™s commute, the system sends the report directly to their cell phone for review.#ai #technews #innovation #podcast #waterloo #health #healthtech #computerscience #startrek

If you recently had trouble figuring out if an image of a person is real or generated through artificial intelligence (AI), you're not alone.A new study from University of Waterloo researchers found that people had more difficulty than was expected distinguishing who is a real person and who is artificially generated.The Waterloo study saw 260 participants provided with 20 unlabeled pictures: 10 of which were of real people obtained from Google searches, and the other 10 generated by Stable Diffusion or DALL-E, two commonly used AI programs that generate images.Participants were asked to label each image as real or AI-generated and explain why they made their decision. Only 61 per cent of participants could tell the difference between AI-generated people and real ones, far below the 85 per cent threshold that researchers expected.#ai #technews #innovation #podcast #waterloo #dalle2 #research

Speaker: Sarah CenDate: Monday, April 1st, 2024Time: 10:30 AM - 11:30 AMLocation: DC 1304Title: Paths to AI AccountabilityAbstract: We have begun grappling with difficult questions related to the rise of AI, including: What rights do individuals have in the age of AI? When should we regulate AI and when should we abstain? What degree of transparency is needed to monitor AI systems? These questions are all concerned with AI accountability: determining who owes responsibility and to whom in the age of AI.In this talk, I will discuss the two main components of AI accountability, then illustrate them through a case study on social media. Within the context of social media, I will focus on how social media platforms filter (or curate) the content that users see. I will review several methods for auditing social media, drawing from concepts and tools in hypothesis testing, causal inference, and LLMs.Speaker Bio: Sarah Cen is a final-year PhD student at MIT in the Electrical Engineering and Computer Science Department advised by Professor Aleksander MÄ…dry and Professor Devavrat Shah.Sarah utilizes methods from machine learning, statistical inference, causal inference, and game theory to study responsible computing and AI policy. Previously, she has written about social media, trustworthy algorithms, algorithmic fairness, and more. She is currently interested in AI auditing, AI supply chains, and IP Law x Gen AI.#ai #MITResearch #TechEthics  #ResponsibleAI #MachineLearning #TechTalk #GameTheory #aiethics #FutureOfAI #innovate #DataScience #intellectualproperty #aigovernance #TechLecture #UniversityOfWaterloo #TechInnovation

VP Arya has been quite busy in the last few weeks. From travelling to different conferences and indulging us here in Comms by filming some videos, he'd like to share some of what he has been up to! First and foremost Arya recently met with a group of other student leaders to set up the new OUSA (Ontario Undergraduate Student Alliance) board for 2024-2025 and is thrilled to share that he was elected to the board as the VP of Finance and the vice chair of the board. This allows WUSA to have some influence on what happens at the provincial level and allows your voices to be heard at a higher level. This board has met a few times since his initial election to the board, where he has had the opportunity to meet the the VP's of the Western Student Council and Laurier's Student Union. At some of the subsequent meetings this board has set up their goals for advocacy this year which include priorities such as housing, investing in PSE, food insecurity with specific lenses and recommendation for each area. Arya also spent some time with the President of WUSA, Nick, going to StudentCare where their goal was to look into expanding your insurance to cover gender affirming health care as well as reviewing the current plan that is offered to students through WUSA. Finally, Arya spent some time at CASA (Canadian Alliance of Student Associations), where he was exploring possible future collaborations between our organizations on federal advocacy initiatives. On the side, Arya has spent some time with the Comms team filming some content, so stay tuned

Please see our statement on the encampment on campus. Swipe through â¡ï¸â€” We are aware of an encampment set up on the Grad House green on Waterlooâ€™s main campus. The Waterloo Undergraduate Student Association (WUSA) supports the right of all students, faculty, and staff to freely and peacefully assemble, express their views, and make their voices heard. We will continue to encourage the University to protect studentsâ€™ right to peaceful protest and maintain a safe space for all students, regardless of their backgrounds or beliefs. We encourage you to ask questions to learn more about whatâ€™s happening both in the Middle East and on university campuses across Canada and the US. Itâ€™s important to stay informed, seek out reliable sources, and have meaningful, respectful conversations with your peers. Be compassionate, even when you have differing views or opinions. WUSA denounces violence and the incitement of hate towards any group, including anti-Palestinian racism, antisemitism, or Islamophobia. We recognize the impact that the on-going war in Israel and Palestine has on the mental well-being of many of our community members. If you are struggling or need support, please reach out to the resources available to you. WUSA offers support such as Empower Me, where you can find someone to talk to 24/7. You can also reach out to Campus Wellness and Counselling Services or find your community through one of our many student clubs and services.
